shared_text:
Dickinson Education Foundation
September 10 at 11:30 AM ¬∑

Golf Ball Purchase Options:
- Choose to keep the ball
- Donate the ball to student(s)
- Donate the ball to teachers(s)
How it works:
Each golf ball purchased will receive an assigned number, the golf balls will be dropped from above onto a target. Each golf ball will be sold for $3.00 per ball, unlimited purchase. The golf ball that is closest to the center target will receive a $2,000 gift card! Second closest to the target will receive a $1,000 gift card. Third closest will receive a $500 gift card. Last day to purchase balls is Friday, September 25,2020.
*Please remember that if you are a Dickinson ISD student and you are one of the three prize winners, you can choose to save your funds for college instead of cashing out your prize now. The Foundation will double the donation therefore you can have a head start on pursuing your higher education goals when you graduate.

2021 will be an important year for the citizens of Texas because it is a Texas legislative year. In addition to representation in Washington and Austin, schools, hospitals, homes, disaster relief, voting, and jobs are dependent on good and accurate data from the census.

A complete and accurate count of residents in Dickinson ISD will ensure that we have the funding needed for our growing school district for the years to come. We have one month left to count every Texan, and in so many ways, a successful census count will positively impact the lives of Texas‚Äôs children.

Last week the Texas self-response rate was 59.6% which ranks 39th among the 50 states and territories. It is estimated that well over 4 million Texans are still uncounted.

Go to https://my2020census.gov to complete your questionnaire today.

We invite you to participate in our Gator Golf Ball Drop fundraiser! This promotion is intended to bring awareness to our Gator students who are seeking scholarships for their higher education. On October 2, we will announce the winners during halftime of the Homecoming game at Sam Vitanza Stadium. Deadline to purchase is September 25. You do not need to be present to win.

All purchases must be made through Eventbrite:

post_text:
Help Dickinson Education Foundation PAY IT FORWARD!

On August 26, our neighbors on the Gulf Coast of Louisiana were severely impacted by the force of Category 4 Hurricane Laura.

Dickinson Education Foundation was generously assisted by many of our neighbors in Louisiana during the aftermath of Hurricane Harvey. This is our opportunity to pay it forward.

We will be accepting monetary donations to assist Calcasieu Parish Public Schools Calcasieu Parish School Board in Lake Charles, Louisiana. CPPS have reported damage to 97% of their school buildings and facilities. At the conclusion of the fundraiser, DISD Education Foundation will send all donations collected to CPPS.

Please see the fundraising campaign on our Facebook page to make your donation. www.facebook.com/DISDedf

We will accept donations through October 1, 2020.
Please, no physical donations at this time.

We are aware that many of our students using a district provided device are having access difficulty with ClassLink. DISD, as well as many other school districts, are working with the vendor to resolve this issue. For now, please use the steps below to help with access:
1. Check parental controls on personal network settings (remove proxy blocking).
2. Bypass ClassLink and go straight to classroom.google.com to access student assignments.

Currently, the digital highway has a major traffic issue, and we are working diligently to resolve it as quickly as possible for students in DISD. Your patience is greatly appreciated.

If you have other technology problems, please contact the Technology Help Desk at helpdesk@dickinsonisd.org.

Dickinson ISD is very grateful that our community was spared from the devastation caused by Hurricane Laura. We are blessed to have no destruction and no loss of power to our homes and our district facilities. Dickinson ISD will reopen tomorrow, Friday, August 28, and remote instruction will continue as scheduled.

Monday, Aug. 31, all Special Programs small groups will begin as planned; however, because of the closure, the transition of PreK and Kindergarten will be delayed. All planning will be completed Friday and Monday, and we will welcome all PreK and kindergarten students registered for Face-to-Face instruction on Tuesday, Sept. 1.

*Dickinson ISD CLOSURE UPDATE*

Dickinson Independent School District will have an early release today at noon to allow employees and families time to prepare for Hurricane Laura.

Here is our current plan:

- Students who are on campus today will be dismissed at 11:00 a.m. and all staff will be released at 12:00.
- DISD will have a full-day closure on Wednesday, August 26 and Thursday, August 27.
(There will be no remote instruction on Wednesday or Thursday.)
- A decision regarding Friday, August 28 will be announced on Thursday.

Dickinson ISD will keep you informed, and it is our goal to resume teaching and learning as soon as possible. Please be safe. #GatorsBetterTogether

Parents who are coming today or tomorrow for device distribution at Kranz Junior High need to bring the student ID card or lunch card for each child. If you do not have either one of these cards, please write the child's name on an index card or piece of paper. Having this information ready when you arrive will help speed the process.

Reminder, today's device distribution from 3-7 p.m. at Kranz Junior High is for any student with a last name beginning with A-J that was unable to receive a device yesterday. The device distribution for tomorrow, Saturday, August 22, is for last name K-P from 8-11:30 a.m. and last name Q-Z from 12:30-4 p.m. In order to pick up a device, the parent must have completed a device needs survey this summer. If you did not complete a device needs survey, you must contact your child's campus on Monday, August 24 to make arrangements to receive a device.

On August 24 we will welcome our students virtually and on September 14 we will welcome face-to-face students back to our campuses. We understand that you and your Gators may be feeling weary about the school year to come. One of our teacher from Gator Nation, Mrs. Doherty from Lobit Middle School, wrote and illustrated this book "Welcome Back" with our Gators in mind. It addresses concerns that students may have about coming back to school during a pandemic.

The Dickinson Education Foundation is selling copies of "Welcome Back" for $12 at the Education Support Center as well as online. Your purchase benefits the foundation's mission of supporting teachers and students by providing teaching grants and scholarships.

Click here to purchase online: http://www.dickinsonisd.org/page/edfoundation.payments

*REMOTE INSTRUCTION INFORMATION*

Dickinson ISD has been busy this summer developing plans for Remote Instruction for the 2020-2021 school year.

Lee Courville, Deputy Superintendent for Educational Services, developed five video messages to breakdown the Remote Instruction Model for each grade level in Dickinson ISD.

The purpose of the videos are to provide parents, students and the community in Dickinson ISD with an understanding of the Remote Instruction Model in Dickinson ISD, what it will look like and what parents and students can expect when we return for the 2020-2021 school year.

We understand parents have a very important decision to make regarding the choice of Face-to-Face or Remote Instruction, and we want them to have the the information needed to make the right decision for their children and family.

To view the Remote Instruction videos, visit our website here: http://www.dickinsonisd.org/page/pi.Remote%20Instruction%20Information

post_text:
Have you registered your student for school this year yet?

It is vital for every family to complete registration before the Friday, August 14 deadline. This process ensures that we have the correct information on file for each student, which is very important because the first day of school will be Remote Instruction. Teachers must have the ability to reach out on the first day of school.

In addition, parents will be selecting if they want their students to participate in Face-to-Face Instruction on campus when it is available or remain in Remote Instruction.

If parents do not make a choice by August 14, then they will be committing to Face-to-Face Instruction starting September 14.

We highly encourage parents to complete online registration as soon as possible.

Please visit here for more information: http://www.dickinsonisd.org/page/article/576

If you have questions or trouble accessing Skyward, please contact your child's campus.

We are deeply saddened to learn of the passing of former Dickinson ISD Board of Trustee, Rosella Scott.

Ms. Scott was a champion for students and education during her 18-year tenure on the board (1996-2014). Her record of accomplishments while serving as both a Trustee and Board Secretary include the building of:

- McAdams Junior High,
- Dunbar and Barber Middle Schools,
- Bay Colony, San Leon, and Calder Road Elementary Schools,
- Gillis Education Support Center, and
- Sam Vitanza Stadium.

With the announcement by the Governor that schools will reopen and recent guidance provided by TEA, we want to provide you with information on our current plans for instruction and learning in Dickinson ISD. Please carefully review the link below explaining the two options that will be available for DISD students, and follow the instructions for indicating your choice in Skyward Family Access. The choice you select now will not be final; it will be used as we continue to plan for the re-opening of our schools.

Click here: http://www.dickinsonisd.org/page/article/570

The 2020-2021 school year brings unique challenges for everyone. Our community health data is monitored daily, and as we receive additional guidance from health officials, TEA, and Governor Abbott, the plans we are making now may be changed. Many, across the district, are working diligently to provide a reopening that is safe for all students and staff and a 2020-2021 educational experience that meets the needs of each learner. Your continued patience, flexibility, and support are greatly appreciated.

post_text:
Although our athletic year was cut short, we want to show appreciation and congratulations to our Dickinson Gators Boys Basketball, who advanced to the state final four earlier this year.

Once the team arrived in San Antonio to compete back in March, they were immediately sent back to Dickinson due to the increasing spread of the covid-19 virus. The team was unable to compete and unable to claim the state championship.

These young men and coach Jason Wilson May proudly display their titles from this year: State Final Four Finalist, Regional Champions, Area Champions, Bi-District Champions and 24-6A Champions.

Check out their appreciation billboard going north bound on I-45, past the FM 518 intersection.

Go Gators!

post_text:
Dickinson ISD will continue offering free meals for students through the summer feeding program. The program will stay mostly the same as it has been in place for the COVID-19 meal distributions; however the distribution time will be changing to 10:30-11:30 a.m. Also, no food will be distributed on Monday, May 25, due to the Memorial Day holiday.

Starting Tuesday, May 26 and through the end of June, meals will be available from 10:30-11:30 a.m. Monday, Tuesday and Thursday at both Dickinson High School and K.E. Little Elementary. The food will be distributed through the same grab-and-go drive through process already in place.

The free meals are available to students age 18 and younger. In order to receive the meals, students must be present in the car or the parent must provide a valid student identification for each child.

Meals will be provided for five days with the following schedule:

* Monday ‚Äì 1 breakfast meal and 1 hot lunch meal
* Tuesday ‚Äì 2 breakfast meals and 1 hot lunch meal and 1 cold lunch meal
* Thursday ‚Äì 2 breakfast meals and 1 hot lunch meal and 1 cold lunch meal

post_text:
Spring 2020 Optional End-of-Year Assessment Registration

The Texas Education Agency (TEA) is offering all students the opportunity to participate in free, at-home, optional end-of-year (EOY) tests. The results from this activity will show how well your child has mastered grade-level knowledge and skills this year. These tests results are solely to help you support your child and will not be used for accountability purposes for your student or school.

If you have more than one student testing, you will need to complete a separate registration form for each child. After registering, you can expect to receive an email with your testing instructions, login, and password within 24‚Äì36 hours. From there, follow the link provided to begin your test. Students will have until June 12th to complete their tests.

Click the link to learn more and view the parent toolkit with forms, links and more.
http://www.dickinsonisd.org/page/article/550

Dickinson Education Foundation
May 8 at 1:39 PM ¬∑

Join us as we recognize our Dickinson Education Foundation Board Members every week to honor their contributions.
Board members are tasked with making decisions on behalf of the foundation and its mission. They ensure that programs and events run smooth by volunteering their time to help do things like event setup, registrations, sponsorship recruitments, teaching grants and scholarship, and representing the foundation at various community forums.

This week we would like to introduce you to one of our board President, Diane Mackey!

Diane is a Dickinson Gradate and she was also a founding board member of the board in 2007. Diane is a mother of two teachers and the owner of Mackey Mechanical, a company that sponsors many events to support DISD.

Thank you Diane for your service to the Dickinson ISD Education Foundation.

post_text:
Starting Monday, May 4, Dickinson ISD will offer free meal distribution at two locations. Dickinson High School, which has been the site of the free meal distribution since March, will remain a distribution site. In addition, the meals will also be distributed in a drive-thru setup at K.E. Little Elementary in the bus lane area by the cafeteria entrance.

The free meals are available to students age 18 and younger three days per week from 11 a.m.-12 p.m. In order to receive the meals, students must be present in the car or the parent must provide a valid student identification for each child.

Meals will be provided for five days with the following schedule:

* Monday ‚Äì 1 breakfast meal and 1 hot lunch meal
* Tuesday ‚Äì 2 breakfast meals and 1 hot lunch meal and 1 cold lunch meal
* Thursday ‚Äì 2 breakfast meals and 1 hot lunch meal and 1 cold lunch meal

post_text: Today is School Lunch Hero Day, and we want to take this opportunity to celebrate our outstanding Dickinson ISD Food and Nutrition heroes. In addition to preparing healthy food and adhering to strict federal and state guidelines, they go above and beyond to provide breakfast and lunch meals for our students while we remained closed for COVID-19. They arrive early each morning to prepare meals and then transport the meals outside for drive-thru pick up. Each day, they do this with big smiles on their faces. We are very blessed in Dickinson ISD to have hard-working, caring, and committed FNS staff. Today and every day, they are School Lunch Heroes. Thank you FNS for all you do for students and staff!!!!

post_text:
Congratulations to the Dickinson High School Student Council for recently being named an Outstanding Student Council by the Texas Association of Student Councils (TASC). The honor is based on documentation of student council organization, specific project areas, participation in TASC programs, and an evaluation by the school administrator.

"The achievement serves as a benchmark for what a well-rounded student council in Texas should do to be effective. This is truly a significant accomplishment," said TASC in the notification letter. "As of April 19, only 337 student councils in Texas earned this recognition in 2019-2020. You are in an elite group," they added.

Congratulations DHS Student Council students and sponsors. #GatorPride

REMINDER:
As of April 20th, the Dickinson ISD Food and Nutrition Department has transitioned to providing meals three days each week. This move helps limit the exposure of our FNS staff as much as possible while still providing nutritious meals to our students. Meals will be provided for five days with the following schedule:

* Monday ‚Äì 1 breakfast meal and 1 hot lunch meal
* Tuesday ‚Äì 2 breakfast meals and 1 hot lunch meal and 1 cold lunch meal
* Thursday ‚Äì 2 breakfast meals and 1 hot lunch meal and 1 cold lunch meal

Meals will be distributed from 11 a.m.-12 p.m. at Dickinson High School (Owens Drive side) for all DISD students. In order to receive the meals, students must be present in the car or the parent must provide a valid student identification for each child.

Dickinson High School 2019-2020 Yearbook Update
The 2019-2020 yearbook is complete and waiting to be printed. The printing plant in Dallas is closed until April 30 by the order of a Dallas County judge, and hopes to return to regular operation in May, but until then, printing is on hold. Once the production process resumes, it will take several weeks for the books to be completed and shipped. More information will come later about how to pick up pre-ordered books, but please do not worry -- there will be a yearbook! It will just arrive later than normal. And if you did not order yet, a limited number of copies are still available at www.balfour.com. Search for Dickinson High School under ‚ÄúShop My School‚Äù and select yearbooks. It‚Äôs that easy! Please email the yearbook adviser at hbooth@dickinsonisd.org with any questions.

post_text:
In Dickinson ISD we are committed to the health and safety of our students and staff, and this includes mental and emotional health. Today, I want to tell you about the Mental Health Wellness Support System that has been created this year thanks to a generous grant we received from Rebuild Texas. Our comprehensive system is called Gator Wellness, and it is available to our students, staff, families, and community.

Through Gator Wellness, we focus on social emotional learning, resiliency, relationship building, trauma informed practices, and overall wellness. Our professional school counselors, licensed professional counselors and licensed specialists in school psychology have attended many hours of specialized training on a wide variety of topics throughout the year. They have used this training to create a three-tiered mental health support system that includes proactive and preventative responses and resources, mental health first aid and crisis response.

ATTENTION PARENTS:
Beginning Monday, April 20, the Dickinson ISD Food and Nutrition Services Department will be transitioning to providing meals three days a week. The move is to limit the exposure of our FNS staff as much as possible while still providing nutritious meals to our students. Students will still receive enough meals for five days. The new meal distribution schedule is:

¬∑ Monday ‚Äì 1 breakfast meal and 1 hot lunch meal
¬∑ Tuesday ‚Äì 2 breakfast meals, 1 hot lunch meal and 1 cold lunch meal
¬∑ Thursday ‚Äì 2 breakfast meals, 1 hot lunch meal and 1 cold lunch meal

The meal distribution will still take place from 11 a.m.-12 p.m. each of the three days on the back side of Dickinson High School (off Owens Drive) in a drive-thru system. In order to receive the meals, students must be present or the parent must provide valid student identification for each student.

The answers you provide are used ONLY to produce statistics. You are kept anonymous and your personal information is kept confidential. The Census Bureau is not permitted to publicly release your responses in any way that could identify you or anyone else in your home.

To fill out the census now, click here: https://2020census.gov/en/ways-to-respond.html

For more information about the Census, visit: http://www.dickinsonisd.org/page/census2020

If your child is not in the vehicle, be prepared to provide a valid school ID or school ID number. In addition, please make sure your children are securely fastened with seatbelts. We appreciate your cooperation!

The Dickinson High School Gators Varsity Boys Basketball team will play Abilene Wylie in the state semifinals at 8:30 p.m. Friday, March 13 at the Alamodome in San Antonio, Texas. The winner of this game will advance to the state championship game at 8:30 p.m. Saturday, March 14 in the Alamodome against the winner of the Duncanville vs. Brandeis game.

Advance tickets for the semifinals game are $16 cash per Session (which is the 7 and 8:30 games only) and will be sold in the DHS field house from 5-7 p.m. Tuesday, March 10 and 9-11 a.m. Wednesday, March 11. Tickets can also be purchased online for $19 through Ticketmaster. The Alamodome has a clear bag policy. If you would like further information please go to the UIL website.

The team is leaving DHS at 9 a.m. Thursday, March 12 to head to San Antonio. The Gator Nation community is encouraged to come out and cheer for the team to bring home a State Championship by lining FM 517 from DHS to I-45.

GO GATORS!!!!!

The Dickinson High School top 20 Graduates were honored at a banquet at Landry's on Tuesday, March 3. Graduates attended with their parents as well as one teacher. Students each selected a teacher in their lives who has inspired or encouraged them along the way to be a part of their special night.

Honorees were: Daviahna Maria DaNaye Boone, Dawson Boudreax, Caleb Rivers Diamond, Miah Michelle Dilka, Gracie Easly, Samantha Gallo, Andre Garcia, Claire Gregory, Adan Hernandez Zermeno, Logan Krejci, Alonzo Rangel, Tyler Reistetter, Emilie Robinson, Lauren Saunders, Katherine Terrell, Joseph Tran, Benjamin Truong, Andrea Uribe, Jessica Wines, Jared Wood.

Thank you to the Dickinson Education Foundation for sponsoring this event!

#GatorPride
